Sure! Here's an example where we use CSS 3D transformation to make a cube that transitions to a sphere, and changes colors as it rotates.

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="cube"></div>
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.container {
  perspective: 800px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  margin: 50px auto;
}

.cube {
  position: relative;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  transform-style: preserve-3d;
  animation: spin 20s linear infinite;
}

.cube:before, .cube:after {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #50C9C3, #96DEDA);
  transition: transform 1s ease-out;
}

.cube:before {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) translateZ(100px);
}

.cube:after {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) translateZ(100px);
}

.cube.sphere:before {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateX(-100px) rotateY(45deg);
}

.cube.sphere:after {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateY(-100px) rotateX(-45deg);
}

@keyframes spin {
  0% { transform: rotateY(0deg); }
  100% { transform: rotateY(-360deg); }
}

.cube:hover:before {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateX(-100px) rotateY(45deg);
}

.cube:hover:after {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateY(-100px) rotateX(-45deg);
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #FFD152, #FFE59E);
}
```

In this example, we create a container with perspective and a width and height of 200px. Inside the container, we create a cube with width and height of 100% and set `transform-style: preserve-3d` to make it a 3D object. 

We then use pseudo-elements `:before` and `:after` to create the sides of the cube, and set them to rotateY and rotateX respectively. We also use a linear gradient to make the color of the cube change from top to bottom.

When hovering over the cube, the `:before` and `:after` pseudo-elements change their transformation to make the cube transition into a sphere using `rotateX` and `rotateY`. Additionally, we change the linear gradient to create a new color theme.

Finally, we add an animation to rotate the cube 360 degrees around its Y-axis over 20s, and set it to infinite. 

Overall, this creates a visually appealing and engaging animation effect using CSS 3D transformations, transitions, and keyframes.

Sure, I'll provide some guidance on how to handle task priorities in your task scheduler application.

1. Define the Priority class
We can start by defining a Priority class that should contain an ID or name field, a description field to define the priority level, and a color field to easily differentiate between priority levels. Here's an example code snippet:

```
@Entity
public class Priority {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String description;
    private String color;

    // getters and setters
}
```

2. Add priority field to Task entity
Next, we need to add a priority field to the Task entity and link it to the Priority entity using JPA's @ManyToOne annotation. Here's an example code snippet:

```
@Entity
public class Task {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private LocalDateTime dueDateTime;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private Priority priority;

    // getters and setters
}
```

3. Create PriorityRepository and PriorityService
Now we can create a PriorityRepository and PriorityService, similar to the TaskRepository and TaskService classes. The PriorityRepository should extend JpaRepository, and PriorityService should define CRUD methods for Priority entities. Here's an example code snippet for PriorityService:

```
@Service
public class PriorityService {
    private final PriorityRepository priorityRepository;

    @Autowired
    public PriorityService(PriorityRepository priorityRepository) {
        this.priorityRepository = priorityRepository;
    }

    public List<Priority> getAllPriorities() {
        return priorityRepository.findAll();
    }

    public Priority getPriorityById(Long id) {
        return priorityRepository.findById(id)
                .orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("Priority", "id", id));
    }

    public Priority createPriority(Priority priority) {
        return priorityRepository.save(priority);
    }

    public Priority updatePriority(Long id, Priority priorityDetails) {
        Priority priority = getPriorityById(id);

        priority.setName(priorityDetails.getName());
        priority.setDescription(priorityDetails.getDescription());
        priority.setColor(priorityDetails.getColor());

        return priorityRepository.save(priority);
    }

    public void deletePriority(Long id) {
        priorityRepository.deleteById(id);
    }
}
```

4. Add priority selection to task form
In the user interface, we can add a dropdown or radio button to let users select a priority level when creating or editing a task. You can retrieve the list of priorities from PriorityService and display them in the form. When a user selects a priority level, you can send the corresponding priority ID to the server when creating or updating a task.

With these steps, you should be able to handle task priorities in your task scheduler application. You can customize the Priority class and priority selection UI to fit your specific requirements.

Sure! To extract the minimum element from a binary tree, you can perform an inorder traversal of the tree and keep track of the smallest element found so far. In an inorder traversal, the nodes in the left subtree are visited first, followed by the root node, and then the nodes in the right subtree. Here's an example method that extracts the minimum element from a binary tree:

```java
public static TreeNode extractMin(TreeNode root) {
    if (root == null) {
        return null;
    }

    TreeNode minNode = findMin(root);
    if (minNode.parent == null) { // minNode is the root
        if (minNode.right == null) {
            return null; // tree is now empty
        } else {
            minNode.right.parent = null;
            return minNode.right; // return new root
        }
    } else if (minNode.right == null) { // minNode has no right child
        if (minNode == minNode.parent.left) {
            minNode.parent.left = null;
        } else {
            minNode.parent.right = null;
        }
        return root; // unchanged
    } else { // minNode has a right child
        minNode.right.parent = minNode.parent;
        if (minNode == minNode.parent.left) {
            minNode.parent.left = minNode.right;
        } else {
            minNode.parent.right = minNode.right;
        }
        return root; // unchanged (except for root node)
    }
}

private static TreeNode findMin(TreeNode node) {
    while (node.left != null) {
        node = node.left;
    }
    return node;
}
```

In this code, `TreeNode` represents a node in the binary tree and has three fields: `left`, `right`, and `parent`, representing the left child, right child, and parent of the node, respectively. The `extractMin` method first calls the `findMin` method to find the node with the minimum value in the tree. If this node is the root of the tree, then we need to update the root accordingly: if the root has a right child, then we make the root's right child the new root; otherwise, the tree is now empty. If the node with the minimum value is not the root, then we need to remove it from the tree and adjust its parent's child pointers accordingly. If the node has a right child, then we replace it with its right child and adjust the child's parent pointer. If the node has no right child, then we simply remove it from the tree by updating its parent's child pointer.

